                <h2>Problem Background: Is Your Creative Actually Selling?</h2>
<p>In Meta advertising, marketers often encounter this dilemma: creatives with high click-through rates and significant spend generate few conversion orders. These creatives "can run" but "cannot sell." Conversely, some creatives have low cost-per-click and scale quickly, yet fail to drive actual sales. There are also cases where creatives have decent conversion rates but too narrow an audience, causing them to exhaust reach within days.</p>
<p>The key to solving these issues lies in establishing a clear review framework. This SOP manual breaks creative review into three core steps, helping you complete an effective creative assessment within 30 minutes.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Step 1: Confirm Prerequisites—Ensure Data Cleanliness</h2>
<p>Before starting the review, verify these three prerequisites:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Conversion tracking is properly configured</strong>: Confirm Meta Pixel or Conversions API is correctly installed with no duplicate event counting</li>
<li><strong>Reasonable data time window</strong>: Analyze data with ≥ 3 days of delivery and cumulative spend ≥ daily budget × 3</li>
<li><strong>Excluded testing period volatility</strong>: Data from the first 24-48 hours is typically unstable; start counting from day 3</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>If the data volume is too small (e.g., total spend under $50), the review conclusions will have limited value. Continue observing and accumulate more data.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Step 2: Establish Evaluation Coordinates—Four Key Metrics</h2>
<p>To differentiate "can run" from "can sell," focus on these four metrics:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Metric</th>
<th>Definition</th>
<th>"Can Run" Benchmark</th>
<th>"Can Sell" Benchmark</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CTR (Click-through rate)</td>
<td>Clicks / Impressions</td>
<td>≥ 1.5% (Feed)</td>
<td>Not a core threshold</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CVR (Conversion rate)</td>
<td>Conversions / Clicks</td>
<td>Not a core threshold</td>
<td>≥ 1% (e-commerce), ≥ 3% (App installs)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CPA (Cost per acquisition)</td>
<td>Spend / Conversions</td>
<td>≤ 120% of target CPA</td>
<td>≤ 100% of target CPA</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Frequency</td>
<td>Avg. times same user sees ad</td>
<td>≤ 3 times / week</td>
<td>Supplementary reference</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Key Decision Logic:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>High CTR + Low CVR</strong>: Creative "can run" but "cannot sell"—issue lies in landing page or audience targeting</li>
<li><strong>High CVR + Low CTR</strong>: Creative quality is decent, but reach is limited—test new placements or bidding strategies</li>
<li><strong>Both CTR and CVR low</strong>: Creative itself has problems—pause or significantly revise</li>
<li><strong>Both CTR and CVR high</strong>: Quality creative—prioritize scaling</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Step 3: Execute the Review—Standardized Decision Process</h2>
<h3>Task 1: Pull Data</h3>
<p>In Meta Ads Manager, export the following data by ad set:<br />
- Impressions, clicks, CTR<br />
- Conversions (by your core event), CVR<br />
- Total spend, CPA, ROAS</p>
<h3>Task 2: Cross-reference Decision Matrices</h3>
<p><strong>Matrix A: Identify Creative Type by Metric Combinations</strong></p>
<pre><code>High CTR (≥1.5%) + High CVR (≥1%) = Potential creative, scale and test
High CTR + Low CVR = Traffic creative, optimize landing page or targeting
Low CTR + High CVR = Precision creative, test new placements or expand targeting
Low CTR + Low CVR = Problematic creative, pause or recreate
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Matrix B: Determine Continuation by ROAS Thresholds</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>ROAS ≥ 120% of target: Continue scaling, maintain current settings</li>
<li>ROAS between 80%-120% of target: Maintain status, monitor 3-5 day trends</li>
<li>ROAS between 50%-80% of target: Adjust targeting or bidding, narrow test scope</li>
<li>ROAS &lt; 50% of target: Pause unless there is a clear optimization direction</li>
</ul>
<h3>Task 3: Document and Archive</h3>
<p>After each review, complete the "Creative Review Log" with the following fields:<br />
- Creative ID / Name<br />
- Delivery date range<br />
- Actual values for four key metrics<br />
- Conclusion (can run / can sell / both / needs optimization)<br />
- Next action (scale / pause / retest after optimization)<br />
- Reviewer / Date</p>
<hr />
<h2>Common Review Pitfalls</h2>
<p><strong>Pitfall 1: Drawing conclusions based on CTR alone</strong><br />
High CTR only indicates the creative is attention-grabbing, not that it drives sales. One cross-border e-commerce team ran a creative with 3.2% CTR but only 0.3% CVR,原因是 the product landing page took over 5 seconds to load, causing severe user drop-off.</p>
<p><strong>Pitfall 2: Pausing based on frequency without analysis</strong><br />
Rising frequency may be normal audience coverage behavior. Try expanding new audiences or adjusting creative formats first—don't immediately shut down creatives with conversions.</p>
<p><strong>Pitfall 3: Negating a creative based on short-term data</strong><br />
Observe data for at least 5-7 days before making judgments. Individual day fluctuations may result from competitive environment changes or budget caps.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Recommended Next Steps</h2>
<p>After completing this review, consider:</p>
<ol>
<li>Prioritize handling "can run but cannot sell" creatives (high CTR + low CVR)—first check landing pages and audience targeting</li>
<li>Include "both" creatives in your scaling test list—increase budget by 20%-50%</li>
<li>Schedule a fixed weekly review time (e.g., Friday afternoon) to build consistency</li>
</ol>
<p>If you find creatives consistently underperforming during reviews, feel free to contact the 以渔数媒 team. We can help diagnose issues with account structure, targeting settings, or conversion tracking configuration.</p>
